After dissolution, a statutory trust continues its existence as a statutory trust, but may not carry on any activities except as is appropriate to wind up and liquidate its activities and affairs, including:
Collecting the assets of the trust;
Disposing of the properties of the trust that will not be distributed in kind to beneficial owners of the trust;
Discharging or making provision for discharging the liabilities of the trust, including entering into agreements with creditors for the satisfaction thereof;
Distributing the remaining property of the trust in accordance with KRS 386A.8-080; and
Doing every other act necessary to wind up and liquidate the trustâ€™s activities and affairs.

The dissolution of a statutory trust does not:
Prevent the commencement of a proceeding by or against the trust in its name;
Abate or suspend a proceeding by or against the trust pending on the effective date of dissolution;
Transfer title to the trustâ€™s property;
Terminate the authority of the registered agent of the statutory trust;
Abate or suspend KRS 386A.3-040; or
Abate or suspend KRS 386A.4-020.
